Deng2014

Wancen Mu, Hirak Sarkar, Avi Srivastava, Kwangbom Choi, Rob Patro, Michael I. Love

Feb 1, 2021

Abstract

Airpart identifies sets of genes displaying differential cell-type-specific allelic imbalance across cell types or states, utilizing single-cell allelic counts. It makes use of a generalized fused lasso with binomial observations of allelic counts to partition cell types by their allelic imbalance. Alternatively, a nonparametric method for partitioning cell types is offered. The package includes a number of visualizations and quality control functions for examining single cell allelic imbalance datasets.

Load data

First, we load the preprocessed Deng 2014 data. It includes one maternal allelic counts(b6) and paternal allelic counts(cast) which was derived after removing some low quality cells indicated in the previous paper. celltype is a character vector of all cell types.

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(SingleCellExperiment))
load("../data/Deng.rda")
cell_meta_unique <- c("zy","early2cell","mid2cell","late2cell","4cell","8cell","16cell","earlyblast","midblast","lateblast") 
order_of_development <- order(match(celltype,cell_meta_unique))
assay.list<-list(a1=b6[,order_of_development],a2=cast[,order_of_development])
coldata<-data.frame(x=factor(celltype[order_of_development],levels=cell_meta_unique))
sce<-SingleCellExperiment(assays=assay.list, colData=coldata)

Now define cell filtering automatically or users can manually filter out based on sum,detected and spikePercent.

keep_cell <- (
  cellQCmetrics$filter_sum & # sufficient features (genes)
  cellQCmetrics$filter_detected & # sufficient molecules counted
  cellQCmetrics$filter_spike  # sufficient features expressed compared to spike genes, high quality cells
) 
table(keep_cell)
## keep_cell
## FALSE  TRUE 
##     2   229
sce<-sce[,keep_cell]

QC on genes

Note that we require genes expressed in at least 25% cells within each cell types.

featureQCmetric<-featureQC(sce,spike = "Ercc",sd = 0.03)
keep_feature<-(featureQCmetric$filter_celltype &
                 featureQCmetric$filter_sd &
                 featureQCmetric$filter_spike)
table(keep_feature)
## keep_feature

Gene clustering

We provide two methods for gene clustering. Gaussian mixture modeling was used in this case. Hierarchical clustering is an alternative way for clustering.

Exclude chromosome X genes

Sex typeing allelic imbalance are excluded because we want to focus on genetically-driven AI. Looking [Larsson2019] vignette, GMM can actually successfully detected chr x and some imprinted genes in one gene cluster as below figure shows there are monoallelic pattern among fibroblast cells but in a coordinate way. So samilar in this dataset, we redo the gene cluster step after removing all the genes on chromosome X.

load("../data/mm9_genome.rda")
gene_chrx<- unname(g$sym[which(seqnames(g)=="chrX")])
sce <- sce[-which(rownames(sce)%in%gene_chrx),]

1. Gaussian Mixture modeling

Gaussian mixture modeling is the default method for gene clustering. The scatter plot is shown based on top 2 PCs of the smoothed allelic ratio data. The argument plot=FALSE can be used to avoid showing the plot. We have found gene clusters more spread out, more extreme allelic imbalance they have.

sce<-geneCluster(sce, G=c(8))
## model-based optimal number of clusters: 8

metadata(sce)$geneCluster
## [1]  943 1444  922  257  827  212   26   48

Simple summary table of alleic ratio

Quickly look at the weighted mean of allelic ratio for each gene cluster. Identify the interested gene cluster. Note that we recommend users only run airpart when the largest ordered allelic ratio difference > 0.05 for speed concerns. We find that the allelic ratio of most of the gene clusters in such cases (small absolute allelic ratio differences) wont provide enough evidence to detect differential allelic imbalance.

Because we are modlling including zygote that mainly involves maternal effect, we find out all clusters exists differential alleic imbalance because weighted allelic ratio mean all really close to 0.

summary<-summaryAllelicRatio(sce)
sapply(1:length(summary), function(i) {
  inst <- summary[[i]]
  inst_order <- inst[order(inst$weighted.mean), ]
  max(diff(inst_order$weighted.mean)) > 0.05
})
## [1] TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE

Hence, we remove the zygote and early2cell cell types and redo the analysis to lower the maternal effect and try to find any meaningful gene sets.

sce <- sce[,sce$x%in%cell_meta_unique[3:10]]
sce$x <- factor(sce$x,cell_meta_unique[3:10])
sce<-geneCluster(sce, G=seq(4,20,4))
## model-based optimal number of clusters: 16

Here we use gene cluster 10 as an example. Since it has higher dispersion, we will use nonparametric approach to partitioning the cell types.

Modeling using non-paramateric method

airpart offers a method for partitioning cell types using non-parametric method because we find that when the allelic counts deviates strongly from a binomial (e.g.large over-dispersion, small values of theta). we have implemented wherein all pairs cell types are compared with Mann-Whitney-Wilcoxon rank sum tests. Cell types are merged based on their similarity of allelic ratios, accounting for excess variability on the ratio from low counts.

estDisp(sce,genecluster = 10)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

sce_sub <- wilcoxExt(sce, genecluster = 10,threshold = 10^seq(from=-4,to=-2,by=0.2))
knitr::kable(metadata(sce_sub)$partition,row.names = F)
part x
1 mid2cell
2 late2cell
3 4cell
4 8cell
4 16cell
5 earlyblast
5 midblast
5 lateblast

Heatmap to show the cell types partition:

makeHeatmap(sce_sub,order_by_group = FALSE,show_row_names = T)

Calculating allelic ratio estimate via hierarchical Bayesian modeling

sce_sub <- allelicRatio(sce_sub)

Violin plot to show posterior mean allelic ratios on the y-axis

makeViolin(sce_sub)
## Joining, by = "x"

GO term analysis

Through GO term evaluation, we can find this gene set has several biological processes are significant different with others, such as cell development (GO:0006139) with p.adj=0.0017, lipid modification(GO: 0030258) with p.adj = 0.0160 and cell differentiation (GO:0030154) with p.adj= 0.0233.
